1
00:00:05,000 --> 00:00:07,000
The last session has ended.

2
00:00:07,300 --> 00:00:09,300
The speakers are packing up.

3
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:11,600
The room is clearing out.

4
00:00:11,900 --> 00:00:14,525
And somewhere in the next 48 hours,

5
00:00:14,825 --> 00:00:18,200
you need to send your client a debrief —

6
00:00:18,500 --> 00:00:22,250
how the day ran, how close you were to schedule,

7
00:00:22,550 --> 00:00:25,550
what incidents happened and how they were handled.

8
00:00:25,850 --> 00:00:28,100
Normally that document takes two hours.

9
00:00:28,400 --> 00:00:30,650
You're pulling times from your notes,

10
00:00:30,950 --> 00:00:33,950
cross-referencing with the programme, trying to remember which

11
00:00:34,250 --> 00:00:36,875
AV issue happened in which room and

12
00:00:37,175 --> 00:00:39,175
what the fix was.

13
00:00:39,475 --> 00:00:43,600
The CueDeck Report Generator does all of that in one click.

14
00:00:43,900 --> 00:00:45,900
Let me show you.

15
00:00:46,200 --> 00:00:49,575
The Report Generator is the third AI agent module,

16
00:00:49,875 --> 00:00:51,875
in the AI Agents panel.

17
00:00:52,175 --> 00:00:55,925
It's director-only — same as the other two agents —

18
00:00:56,225 --> 00:00:58,475
because this is a document that

19
00:00:58,775 --> 00:01:02,150
will go to your client or your internal team.

20
00:01:02,450 --> 00:01:05,450
Click Generate Report and the process starts immediately.

21
00:01:05,750 --> 00:01:09,500
CueDeck pulls all the data it needs from the current

22
00:01:09,800 --> 00:01:12,800
event — session records, scheduled versus actual times,

23
00:01:13,100 --> 00:01:16,850
the incident log, everything that happened during the day —

24
00:01:17,150 --> 00:01:20,525
and passes it to Claude to generate the report.

25
00:01:20,825 --> 00:01:24,575
While the report generates you'll see this thinking animation —

26
00:01:24,875 --> 00:01:28,625
five steps cycling through, each one lighting up as the

27
00:01:28,925 --> 00:01:31,925
AI works through that phase of the report.

28
00:01:32,225 --> 00:01:35,600
Session analysis, incident processing, metric calculation, summary drafting, recommendations.

29
00:01:35,900 --> 00:01:38,525
This typically takes fifteen to twenty seconds.

30
00:01:38,825 --> 00:01:41,450
When it finishes, the tabs appear and

31
00:01:41,750 --> 00:01:43,750
the content is ready.

32
00:01:44,050 --> 00:01:46,300
The first tab is Summary —

33
00:01:46,600 --> 00:01:50,350
and this is what I'd open if I were sending

34
00:01:50,650 --> 00:01:52,650
something to a client.

35
00:01:52,950 --> 00:01:55,200
At the top, four stat cards:

36
00:01:55,500 --> 00:01:59,250
total sessions run today, the on-time rate as a percentage,

37
00:01:59,550 --> 00:02:01,800
the average overrun across all sessions,

38
00:02:02,100 --> 00:02:04,725
and the total number of incidents logged.

39
00:02:05,025 --> 00:02:09,150
These are pulled from your actual session data — not estimates.

40
00:02:09,450 --> 00:02:12,450
Below that, two written sections generated by Claude:

41
00:02:12,750 --> 00:02:15,750
an Executive Summary — three to four sentences,

42
00:02:16,050 --> 00:02:19,050
professional tone, suitable for a client email —

43
00:02:19,350 --> 00:02:22,725
and a Technical Performance paragraph covering AV system reliability,

44
00:02:23,025 --> 00:02:25,025
streaming stability, and crew execution.

45
00:02:25,325 --> 00:02:27,950
This is the kind of language that

46
00:02:28,250 --> 00:02:30,500
normally takes thirty minutes to write.

47
00:02:30,800 --> 00:02:33,050
It's already there, it's accurate, and

48
00:02:33,350 --> 00:02:35,975
it's based on what actually happened today.

49
00:02:36,275 --> 00:02:38,900
The Sessions tab is your variance table.

50
00:02:39,200 --> 00:02:42,950
Every session, side by side: planned start time versus actual

51
00:02:43,250 --> 00:02:45,875
start time, and the delta in minutes.

52
00:02:46,175 --> 00:02:48,800
Green deltas mean on time or early.

53
00:02:49,100 --> 00:02:52,850
Orange means a minor overrun — within a few minutes.

54
00:02:53,150 --> 00:02:55,400
Red means it ran significantly late.

55
00:02:55,700 --> 00:02:58,325
You can see at a glance where

56
00:02:58,625 --> 00:03:01,625
the day was tight and where it slipped.

57
00:03:01,925 --> 00:03:05,675
This table is what you'd use for your internal debrief

58
00:03:05,975 --> 00:03:08,225
— understanding which rooms ran well,

59
00:03:08,525 --> 00:03:11,525
which sessions need buffer time added next year,

60
00:03:11,825 --> 00:03:14,450
whether the lunch break was long enough.

61
00:03:14,750 --> 00:03:18,500
It's also useful for invoice justification if you're billing for

62
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:20,800
overtime on a specific room.

63
00:03:21,100 --> 00:03:24,475
The Incidents tab is the log of everything that

64
00:03:24,775 --> 00:03:28,150
was flagged through the Incident Advisor during the day.

65
00:03:28,450 --> 00:03:31,450
Each entry shows the time it was triggered,

66
00:03:31,750 --> 00:03:35,500
the system affected, the location, the description you typed when

67
00:03:35,800 --> 00:03:39,925
you raised it, and the final status — resolved or escalated.

68
00:03:40,225 --> 00:03:43,600
If you had two incidents during the day and

69
00:03:43,900 --> 00:03:47,650
both were resolved on-site, this tab tells that story clearly.

70
00:03:47,950 --> 00:03:50,950
If one was escalated to a senior technician,

71
00:03:51,250 --> 00:03:53,250
that's logged here too.

72
00:03:53,550 --> 00:03:57,300
For a client-facing debrief, this is the section you use

73
00:03:57,600 --> 00:03:59,850
to explain what went wrong and

74
00:04:00,150 --> 00:04:02,150
what was done about it.

75
00:04:02,450 --> 00:04:04,450
Transparent, timestamped, factual.

76
00:04:04,750 --> 00:04:08,875
The fourth tab is where the report really earns its place.

77
00:04:09,175 --> 00:04:11,425
This is the AI Narrative —

78
00:04:11,725 --> 00:04:14,350
a full written debrief generated by Claude,

79
00:04:14,650 --> 00:04:18,025
covering how the day ran in plain professional English.

80
00:04:18,325 --> 00:04:20,575
It synthesises everything: the session count,

81
00:04:20,875 --> 00:04:23,875
the schedule adherence, the incidents, the technical environment,

82
00:04:24,175 --> 00:04:26,175
and the crew's execution.

83
00:04:26,475 --> 00:04:30,225
The result reads like something written by a senior production

84
00:04:30,525 --> 00:04:32,775
manager reflecting on the event —

85
00:04:33,075 --> 00:04:36,450
because in a sense, that's exactly what it is.

86
00:04:36,750 --> 00:04:39,375
Below the narrative, a numbered recommendations list.

87
00:04:39,675 --> 00:04:41,925
Four to five items, specific and

88
00:04:42,225 --> 00:04:45,225
actionable: add buffer time before the closing keynote,

89
00:04:45,525 --> 00:04:49,275
assign a dedicated stream monitor for events above five hundred

90
00:04:49,575 --> 00:04:54,450
online attendees, confirm EDID compatibility for the main stage switcher before doors open.

91
00:04:54,750 --> 00:04:57,750
Real recommendations based on what actually happened today.

92
00:04:58,050 --> 00:05:00,300
Once you're happy with the report,

93
00:05:00,600 --> 00:05:03,225
two export options are in the footer.

94
00:05:03,525 --> 00:05:07,275
Copy Text puts the full report onto your clipboard as

95
00:05:07,575 --> 00:05:10,950
plain text — ready to paste into an email,

96
00:05:11,250 --> 00:05:13,875
a Google Doc, or a Notion page.

97
00:05:14,175 --> 00:05:18,300
Print / PDF opens the browser print dialog, formatted for print.

98
00:05:18,600 --> 00:05:21,975
From there you can save as a PDF and

99
00:05:22,275 --> 00:05:24,525
attach it to your client debrief,

100
00:05:24,825 --> 00:05:27,450
or print it for your own records.

101
00:05:27,750 --> 00:05:30,000
The report includes the event name,

102
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:32,550
date, and a generated timestamp —

103
00:05:32,850 --> 00:05:35,850
so it's clearly identified and ready to send.

104
00:05:36,150 --> 00:05:38,400
Three main use cases for this.

105
00:05:38,700 --> 00:05:41,325
Client debrief: copy the Executive Summary and

106
00:05:41,625 --> 00:05:45,000
the Incidents log and send it within the hour.

107
00:05:45,300 --> 00:05:47,300
Clients appreciate fast, professional follow-through.

108
00:05:47,600 --> 00:05:52,475
Internal review: use the Sessions variance table in your next production planning meeting.

109
00:05:52,775 --> 00:05:57,650
The overruns tell you where to add buffer in the schedule next time.

110
00:05:57,950 --> 00:06:01,700
Invoice justification: if you're billing for additional crew time or

111
00:06:02,000 --> 00:06:04,250
technical callouts, the incident log and

112
00:06:04,550 --> 00:06:07,925
timestamps give you the documentation to back it up.

113
00:06:08,225 --> 00:06:10,225
One click.

114
00:06:10,525 --> 00:06:12,525
Full report.

115
00:06:12,825 --> 00:06:14,825
Ready to send.

116
00:06:15,125 --> 00:06:18,125
That's the Report Generator — the third and

117
00:06:18,425 --> 00:06:20,425
final AI agent in CueDeck.

118
00:06:20,725 --> 00:06:22,975
Combined with the Incident Advisor and

119
00:06:23,275 --> 00:06:26,650
the Cue Engine, you have an AI co-pilot that

120
00:06:26,950 --> 00:06:29,575
runs with you through the entire event:

121
00:06:29,875 --> 00:06:32,125
prevention before it starts, response when

122
00:06:32,425 --> 00:06:35,050
something breaks, and documentation when it's done.

123
00:06:35,350 --> 00:06:38,725
In the next episode we're getting into signage —

124
00:06:39,025 --> 00:06:41,650
specifically the Timeline and Programme display modes.

125
00:06:41,950 --> 00:06:44,950
If you've ever wanted an attendee-facing screen that

126
00:06:45,250 --> 00:06:48,250
shows the day's schedule in real time and

127
00:06:48,550 --> 00:06:51,925
updates automatically as sessions go live, that's the episode.

128
00:06:52,225 --> 00:06:54,225
I'll see you there.
